            {'title': 'Parasitology', 'body': 'The Cordyceps fungus and many parasitic wasps (Ichneumonidae) reproduce by consuming their hosts alive from the inside, keeping them alive as long as possible to maximise the food source. These are not anomalies but standard, widespread evolutionary strategies, optimised by natural selection for maximum efficiency, not minimum suffering.'},
            {'title': 'Mass Extinctions', 'body': 'Five mass extinction events have wiped out 70-96% of all species at various points, the vast majority before any human or human ancestor existed to witness, learn from, or be "tested" by them. A designer optimising for sentient moral development would not need to kill 96% of marine species in the Permian extinction 252 million years ago.'},
            {'title': 'Random Geographic Distribution of Suffering', 'body': 'Natural disasters, genetic diseases, and childhood cancers are distributed with no correlation to moral merit — devastating earthquakes strike believers and nonbelievers, infants and tyrants, with statistically random geographic and genetic patterns matching plate tectonics and mutation rates, not judgment.'},
            {'title': 'Evolutionary Origin of Suffering Itself', 'body': 'Pain and suffering are themselves evolved adaptations — nervous systems that register damage and motivate avoidance survive better than those that do not. Suffering is not a corruption of a perfect design; it is a functional, naturalistic solution to a survival problem, exactly as evolution predicts and exactly as a designer would not need to implement from scratch.'},
